+
+## Solution
+
+### Selected Variant
+
+Use a focused `src/state/run-doctor.ts` service plus thin `src/cli.ts`
+routing. Rationale: this keeps durability logic beside journal/lock helpers,
+makes diagnosis and repair unit-testable, and avoids bloating CLI parsing or
+creating an oversized recovery subsystem outside the task scope.
+
+### Files to Create or Modify
+
+- `src/state/run-doctor.ts`
+  - Export `doctorRun(options)` returning findings, repair actions, and
+    `hasErrors`.
+  - Parse `journal.jsonl` line-by-line to collect syntax, duplicate
+    `event_id`, non-monotonic `seq`, unknown `kind`, and torn-final-line
+    findings.
+  - Call `replayRunJournal(runDir)` once syntax allows replay; inspect the
+    resulting `RunState` and parsed raw events for replay invariants. Detect
+    events after terminal run records from the raw event stream, not from the
+    replayed terminal-precedence state.
+  - Use `getRunDir()`, `getNodeDir()`, and `getJournalPath()` for paths, and
+    `readLock()` / `isPidAlive()` for lock handling.
+  - Implement repair as journal backup plus temporary-file rename and stale
+    lock removal only after refusal checks pass.
+- `src/state/run-doctor_test.ts`
+  - Build fabricated workflow/run directories with real journal records.
+  - Cover all requested diagnosis and repair cases.
+- `src/cli.ts`
+  - Add `runs doctor --workflow <dir> --run <runId> [--repair] [--json]`.
+  - Print grouped human report or JSON findings and set exit code by errors.
+  - Add the subcommand to help output.
+- `src/cli_test.ts`
+  - Cover help text and JSON output shape through existing CLI test patterns;
+    prefer direct exported helpers for exit-code assertions and use subprocess
+    coverage only where process-level output is required.
+- `documents/requirements-engine.md`,
+  `documents/requirements-engine/01-execution-model.md`,
+  `documents/index.md`
+  - Register FR-E83 and point acceptance at the new tests.
+- `documents/design-engine/04-data-and-logic.md` and, if needed,
+  `documents/design-engine/02-engine-modules-flow.md`
+  - Add concise design notes for doctor orchestration and repair policy.
+
+### Implementation Approach
+
+1. RED: add `run-doctor_test.ts` fixtures for clean, torn-tail, corrupted,
+   filesystem, lock, repair, refusal, and JSON cases. Run focused tests and
+   confirm they fail because the module is absent.
+2. GREEN: implement `run-doctor.ts` with structured findings:
+   `{ severity, code, message, evidence_path }`.
+3. RED/GREEN for CLI: add CLI tests, then route `runs doctor` in `cli.ts`.
+4. REFACTOR: keep parsing helpers private and deterministic; keep all repair
+   decisions in one refusal predicate. Evaluate every refusal before creating
+   backups, rewriting journals, or removing locks so repair is all-or-nothing.
+5. Docs: add FR-E83 SRS/index entries and compact SDS notes.
+6. CHECK: run `deno task check`.
+
+### Error Handling
+
+Doctor reports every finding it can prove. It refuses repair if the selected
+run is live or if the journal has any error other than a torn final line. It
+performs every refusal check before modifying either journal or lock artifacts.
+Filesystem and JSON errors include the evidence path. Atomic journal repair
+writes `journal.jsonl.tmp`, then renames it over `journal.jsonl` after creating
+`journal.jsonl.bak`.
+
+### Verification Commands
+
+- `deno task test -- run-doctor_test`
+- `deno task test -- cli_test run-doctor_test`
+- `deno task check`
+
+## Follow-ups
+
+- Batch mode across all runs is out of scope.
+- Journal compaction is out of scope.
